   377→## Caveats
   382→By default, `input-otp` handles password managers for you.
   383→The password manager badges should be automatically shifted to the right side.
   384→
   385→However, if you still want to block password managers, please disable the `pushPasswordManagerStrategy` and then manually block each PWM.
   386→
   387→```diff
   388→<OTPInput
   389→  // First, disable library's built-in strategy
   390→  // for shifting badges automatically
   391→- pushPasswordManagerStrategy="increase-width"
   392→+ pushPasswordManagerStrategy="none"
   393→  // Then, manually add specifics attributes
   394→  // your password manager docs
   395→  // Example: block LastPass
   396→+ data-lpignore="true" 
   397→  // Example: block 1Password
   398→+ data-1p-ignore="true"
   399→/>
   400→```
   401→</details>
   402→
   403→<details>
   404→<summary>[Setting] If you want to customize the `noscript` CSS fallback</summary>
   405→
   406→By default, `input-otp` handles cases where JS is not in the page by applying custom CSS styles.
   407→If you do not like the fallback design and want to apply it to your own, just pass a prop:
   408→
   409→```diff
   410→// This is the default CSS fallback.
   411→// Feel free to change it entirely and apply to your design system.
   412→const NOSCRIPT_CSS_FALLBACK = `
   413→[data-input-otp] {
   414→  --nojs-bg: white !important;
   415→  --nojs-fg: black !important;
   416→
   417→  background-color: var(--nojs-bg) !important;
   418→  color: var(--nojs-fg) !important;
   419→  caret-color: var(--nojs-fg) !important;
      →…
